\begin_layout Standard
In 2007, while I was working in my first job at JP Morgan - I had been trained
 only to work on rational problems.
 My task at the bank was to improve the methods to calculate credit risk
 exposures for the firm's OTC portfolio.
 I was thrilled - to say the least - at the sophistication involved in what
 I had assumed to be only an accounting activity.
 I worked at JP Morgan for 3 years - to join a trading desk later.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It would be wrong to say that I was tired of reading rules for accounting
 as a trained scientist.
 On the contrary, I only wanted to learn more about financial economics
 - as my understanding of accounting had often led me to a void.
 Reading the Basel III accord, for example, it occurred to me that the rules
 were written in response to the incidents we had talked about in our daily
 meetings - rather than formulation of a new theory.
 Having been presented the issue of risk management always as a rational
 problem had probably hindered my understanding of the economics behind
 Basel principles.
 In 
