\begin_layout Standard
The curiosity drove me to work at trading desks on both sides of the Atlantic.
 During this time, the need to acquire skills that I hadn't been trained
 into were fulfilled by reading and researching online.
 Still, even though calibration of interest rate models and searching for
 arbitrage opportunities in markets had occupied most of my adult life -
 I could not have said that I had appreciated economics at any point.
 It was only until I was in a class on investments taught by Dr Ralph Koijen
 at London Business School - that I realized the true scope of my work in
 research and backtesting.
 Taking further courses in economics and reading Smith, Fisher and Keynes
 on my way back from school, I came to understand that generating alpha
 was a problem far older than I had thought.
 More importantly, I learned how much more the scope of academic research
 needs to be.
 Getting exposed to inputs for buy-side finance after having designed algorithms
 for trading volatility as an asset in my work experience gave me an opportunity
 to be skeptical of the arms race adopted in low-latency trading and appreciate
 how rare can an understanding of basic financial economics can become.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I view my decision to pursue research at the program is a culmination of
 this curiosity and a commitment towards academic output.
 Statistical forecasting and predictive trading do appeal to the mathematician,
 but that at the heart of it all, transactions were simple and their goals
 - fairly non-technical - is of importance to me as a student of economics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At London Business School, I continued to focus on the practical aspects
 rather than mastering models for risk-arbitrage.
 In the investments area, my work involved researching the factor based
 on PPE ratios - and testing out economic claims through backtesting.
 In another writeup, I had explore market-value of risk through simulations
 to find out why carbon trading markets had collapsed.
 I have briefly researched on Burma - to understand issues in political
 economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
My current goal for research in economics is driven by the inputs for investment
 and policy-making.
 With part-time studies I wish to address curiosities that I have had but
 never attempted to provide a public domain for.
 The research I am broadly interested in are liquidity and cross-asset compariso
n of conspicuous consumption in societies.
